answers.body_markdown:
The general solution for this kind of problem is _interfaces_: define a common interface to be implemented by both classes:

```
interface MyObjectsProvider {
  Collection&lt;MyObjects&gt; getAllMyObjects();
}

class Class1 implements MyObjectsProvider {
  @Override
  public Collection&lt;MyObjects&gt; getAllMyObjects() {
    return ...
  }
}

class Class2 implements MyObjectsProvider {
  @Override
  public Collection&lt;MyObjects&gt; getAllMyObjects() {
    return ...
  }
}
```

Usage could be as simple as:

```
MyObjectsProvider variable = anotherVar;
list.addAll(variable.getAllMyObjects());
```

or if the type is unknown and cannot be constrained to the interface:

```
var variable = anotherVar;
if (variable instanceof MyObjectsProvider) {
     list.addAll(((MyObjectsProvider) variable).getAllMyObjects);
}
```

